            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Benjamin Aziz\u2019s life has been a study in quiet deviation from the expected path. Raised in Modesto, he was a child of two worlds: his father, a Lebanese immigrant, filled their home with the aroma of za'atar and the warmth of loud family gatherings, while his Midwestern mother instilled in him a steady, practical calm. Benjamin was a sensitive, observant kid who dreamed of a life bigger than the Central Valley's predictable horizons. He enrolled in college at Sacramento State, vaguely pursuing a degree in communications, but mostly just savoring his escape.\n\nThe turning point came during his sophomore year. His mother was diagnosed with a rapidly progressing form of Multiple Sclerosis. Without a second thought, Benjamin left school and moved back home, becoming her primary caregiver. The world of lecture halls was replaced by one of medication schedules, physical therapy, and the profound, demanding intimacy of tending to a loved one\u2019s decline. He learned patience and a deep well of empathy he never knew he possessed.\n\nAfter his mother passed away two years later, caregiving was no longer just a necessity; it was his vocation. He felt adrift without the structure of purpose it provided. He found a listing for a live-in personal attendant for an elderly widower in San Francisco's Inner Richmond district and took the job. For the past six years, this has been his life. His 0.0-mile commute is the walk from his small bedroom to the living room of Mr. Henderson\u2019s classic Edwardian flat.\n\nHis days are structured and insular, revolving around Mr. Henderson\u2019s needs. He finds freedom in small pockets: an early morning walk through the fog in Golden Gate Park, a quick solo lunch at a Clement Street noodle house, or sketching the neighborhood architecture in a worn notebook. His social life consists of brief, friendly exchanges with the grocer and pharmacists who know him by name. He dreams not of wealth, but of space and time\u2014the time to finish a painting, the space to have a partner over for dinner. He hopes to one day re-enroll at City College, perhaps to study art. Benjamin didn\u2019t find the vibrant, fast-paced San Francisco he once imagined, but in a quiet corner of the city, he has built a meaningful life of service and profound, unspoken connection."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the fluorescent light humming in his Sac State dorm room. His father\u2019s voice on the phone was strained, using a clinical term\u2014*progressive relapse*\u2014that felt alien. Outside, students were shouting, laughing on their way to a party. In that moment, the entire world of keg stands and study groups dissolved into static. There was no decision to make, only a quiet, immediate certainty. His path was no longer heading toward a vague future, but straight back home to Modesto. It was the moment his compass found its true north: his mother.\n\n2.\nHe recalls the specific weight of the silver spoon in his hand as he fed his mother applesauce. Her hands, once steady enough to knead dough, now trembled too much to hold it herself. She was frustrated, but as he brought the spoon to her lips, she looked at him and smiled\u2014a weak, but genuine, flicker of her old self. The profound sadness of her decline was eclipsed by a wave of pure, protective love. This was not a chore; it was the most important work he had ever done. Caregiving became his language.\n\n3.\nAfter the funeral, the house in Modesto was suffocatingly quiet. The routines that had structured his life for two years were gone, leaving a gaping void. He felt utterly adrift, a caregiver with no one to care for. Scrolling aimlessly through job listings one night, he saw it: \"Live-in attendant, quiet widower, Inner Richmond.\" It wasn't the exciting San Francisco of his childhood dreams. It was a lifeline\u2014a quiet harbor, a familiar purpose. He applied without hesitation, trading one form of devotion for another.\n\n4.\nOne Tuesday morning, just after dawn, he was walking through Golden Gate Park. The fog was so thick it swallowed the sound of the city, leaving only the damp smell of eucalyptus and the drip of condensation from the cypress trees. He stopped, completely alone, and pulled out his sketchbook. He didn't draw, just stood there, letting the profound quiet seep into him. This was his San Francisco\u2014not a bustling metropolis, but a private, peaceful space he could hold entirely for himself, a freedom found in the mist.\n\n5.\nMr. Henderson had been silent all day, lost in a memory Benjamin couldn't access. When Benjamin brought him his evening tea, the old man didn\u2019t look up. But as Benjamin set the cup down, Mr. Henderson reached out and rested his frail, papery hand on Benjamin\u2019s for just a second. It wasn't a thank you, but an acknowledgment\u2014a silent, powerful recognition of his presence, his constancy. In that brief touch, six years of quiet service felt seen, valued, and deeply meaningful."
        },
